[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] An **optimizing compiler** is a compiler designed to generate code that is optimized in aspects such as minimizing program execution time, memory usage, storage size, and power consumption.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Optimization is generally implemented as a sequence of **optimizing transformations**, a.k.a.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] **compiler optimizations** – algorithms that transform code to produce semantically equivalent code optimized for some aspect.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Optimization is limited by a number of factors.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Theoretical analysis indicates that some optimization problems are NP-complete, or even undecidable.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Also, producing perfectly *optimal* code is not possible since optimizing for one aspect often degrades performance for another (see: superoptimization).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Optimization is a collection of heuristic methods for improving resource usage in typical programs.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Scope describes how much of the input code is considered to apply optimizations.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Local scope optimizations use information local to a basic block.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Since basic blocks contain no control flow statements, these optimizations require minimal analysis, reducing time and storage requirements.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] However, no information is retained across jumps.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Global scope optimizations, also known as intra-procedural optimizations, operate on individual functions.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] This gives them more information to work with but often makes expensive computations necessary.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Worst-case assumptions need to be made when function calls occur or global variables are accessed because little information about them is available.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Peephole optimizations are usually performed late in the compilation process after machine code has been generated.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] This optimization examines a few adjacent instructions (similar to "looking through a peephole" at the code) to see whether they can be replaced by a single instruction or a shorter sequence of instructions.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] For instance, a multiplication of a value by two might be more efficiently executed by left-shifting the value or by adding the value to itself (this example is also an instance of strength reduction).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Interprocedural optimizations analyze all of a program's source code.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] The more information available, the more effective the optimizations can be.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] The information can be used for various optimizations, including function inlining, where a call to a function is replaced by a copy of the function body.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Link-time optimization (LTO), or whole-program optimization, is a more general class of interprocedural optimization.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] During LTO, the compiler has visibility across translation units which allows it to perform more aggressive optimizations like cross-module inlining and devirtualization.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Machine code optimization involves using an object code optimizer to analyze the program after all machine code has been linked.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Techniques such as macro compression, which conserves space by condensing common instruction sequences, become more effective when the entire executable task image is available for analysis.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Most high-level programming languages share common programming constructs and abstractions, such as branching constructs (if, switch), looping constructs (for, while), and encapsulation constructs (structures, objects).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Thus, similar optimization techniques can be used across languages.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] However, certain language features make some optimizations difficult.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] For instance, pointers in C and C++ make array optimization difficult; see alias analysis.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] However, languages such as PL/I that also support pointers implement optimizations for arrays.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Conversely, some language features make certain optimizations easier.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] For example, in some languages, functions are not permitted to have side effects.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Therefore, if a program makes several calls to the same function with the same arguments, the compiler can infer that the function's result only needs to be computed once.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] In languages where functions are allowed to have side effects, the compiler can restrict such optimization to functions that it can determine have no side effects.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Many optimizations that operate on abstract programming concepts (loops, objects, structures) are independent of the machine targeted by the compiler, but many of the most effective optimizations are those that best exploit special features of the target platform.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Examples are instructions that do several things at once, such as decrement register and branch if not zero.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] The following is an instance of a local machine-dependent optimization.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] To set a register to 0, the obvious way is to use the constant '0' in an instruction that sets a register value to a constant.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] A less obvious way is to XOR a register with itself or subtract it from itself.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] It is up to the compiler to know which instruction variant to use.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] On many RISC machines, both instructions would be equally appropriate, since they would both be the same length and take the same time.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] A potential problem with this is that XOR or subtract may introduce a data dependency on the previous value of the register, causing a pipeline stall, which occurs when the processor must delay execution of an instruction because it depends on the result of a previous instruction.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] However, processors often treat the XOR of a register with itself or the subtract of a register from itself as a special case that does not cause stalls.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Whether particular optimizations can and should be applied may depend on the characteristics of the target machine.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] parameterize machine-dependent factors so that they can be used to optimize for different machines.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] can be optimized for the target CPU and memory.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] System cost or reliability may be more important than the code speed.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] For example, compilers for embedded software usually offer options that reduce code size at the expense of speed.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] The code's timing may need to be predictable, rather than as fast as possible, so code caching might be disabled, along with compiler optimizations that require it.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Optimization includes the following, sometimes conflicting themes.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] If the fast path is taken more often, the result is better overall performance.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Reuse results that are already computed and store them for later use, instead of recomputing them.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Remove unnecessary computations and intermediate values.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Less work for the CPU, cache, and memory usually results in faster execution.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] , less code brings a lower product cost.
