[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Instruction scheduling is an important optimization for modern pipelined processors, which avoids stalls or bubbles in the pipeline by clustering instructions with no dependencies together, while being careful to preserve the original semantics.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Rematerialization recalculates a value instead of loading it from memory, eliminating an access to memory.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] This is performed in tandem with register allocation to avoid spills.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] If several sequences of code are identical, or can be parameterized or reordered to be identical, they can be replaced with calls to a shared subroutine.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] This can often share code for subroutine set-up and sometimes tail-recursion.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] CPUs have smaller subroutine call instructions to access low memory.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] A compiler can save space by using these small calls in the main body of code.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Jump instructions in low memory can access the routines at any address.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] This multiplies space savings from code factoring.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] , restructuring compilers enhance data locality and expose more parallelism by reordering computations.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Space-optimizing compilers may reorder code to lengthen sequences that can be factored into subroutines.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Although many of these also apply to non-functional languages, they either originate in or are particularly critical in functional languages such as Lisp and ML.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] A function call consumes stack space and involves some overhead related to parameter passing and flushing the instruction cache.
