[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] If an expression is carried out both when a condition is met and is not met, it can be written just once outside of the conditional statement.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Similarly, if certain types of expressions (e.g., the assignment of a constant into a variable) appear inside a loop, they can be moved out of it because their effect will be the same no matter if they're executed many times or just once.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] This is also known as total redundancy elimination.
