[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Interprocedural optimization works on the entire program, across procedure and file boundaries.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] It works tightly with intraprocedural counterparts, carried out with the cooperation of a local part and a global part.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Typical interprocedural optimizations are procedure inlining, interprocedural dead-code elimination, interprocedural constant propagation, and procedure reordering.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] As usual, the compiler needs to perform interprocedural analysis before its actual optimizations.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Interprocedural analyses include alias analysis, array access analysis, and the construction of a call graph.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Interprocedural optimization is common in modern commercial compilers from SGI, Intel, Microsoft, and Sun Microsystems.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] For a long time, the open source GCC was criticized for a lack of powerful interprocedural analysis and optimizations, though this is now improving.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Another open-source compiler with full analysis and optimization infrastructure is Open64.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Due to the extra time and space required by interprocedural analysis, most compilers do not perform it by default.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Users must use compiler options explicitly to tell the compiler to enable interprocedural analysis and other expensive optimizations.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] There can be a wide range of optimizations that a compiler can perform, ranging from simple and straightforward optimizations that take little compilation time to elaborate and complex optimizations that involve considerable amounts of compilation time.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] By the 2000s, it was common for compilers, such as Clang, to have several compiler command options that could affect a variety of optimization choices, starting with the familiar `-O2` switch.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] An approach to isolating optimization is the use of so-called post-pass optimizers (some commercial versions of which date back to mainframe software of the late 1970s).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] These tools take the executable output by an optimizing compiler and optimize it even further.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Post-pass optimizers usually work on the assembly language or machine code level (in contrast with compilers that optimize intermediate representations of programs).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] One such example is the Portable C Compiler (PCC) of the 1980s, which had an optional pass that would perform post-optimizations on the generated assembly code.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Another consideration is that optimization algorithms are complicated and, especially when being used to compile large, complex programming languages, can contain bugs that introduce errors in the generated code or cause internal errors during compilation.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Compiler errors of any kind can be disconcerting to the user, but especially so in this case, since it may not be clear that the optimization logic is at fault.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] In the case of internal errors, the problem can be partially ameliorated by a "fail-safe" programming technique in which the optimization logic in the compiler is coded such that a failure is trapped, a warning message issued, and the rest of the compilation proceeds to successful completion.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Early compilers of the 1960s were often primarily concerned with simply compiling code correctly or efficiently, such that compile times were a major concern.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] One notable early optimizing compiler was the IBM FORTRAN H compiler of the late 1960s.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] Another of the earliest and important optimizing compilers, that pioneered several advanced techniques, was that for BLISS (1970), which was described in *The Design of an Optimizing Compiler* (1975).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] By the late 1980s, optimizing compilers were sufficiently effective that programming in assembly language declined.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler-optimization] This co-evolved with the development of RISC chips and advanced processor features such as superscalar processors, out-of-order execution, and speculative execution, which were designed to be targeted by optimizing compilers rather than by human-written assembly code.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] In computing, a **compiler** is software that translates computer code written in one programming language (the *source* language) into another language (the *target* language).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The name "compiler" is primarily used for programs that translate source code from a high-level programming language to a low-level programming language (e.g., assembly language, object code, or machine code) to create an executable program.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] There are many different types of compilers which produce output in different useful forms.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] A *cross-compiler* produces code for a different central processing unit (CPU) or operating system than the one on which the cross-compiler itself runs.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] A *bootstrap compiler* is often a temporary compiler, used for compiling a more permanent or better optimized compiler for a language.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Compilers generally implement these phases as modular components, promoting efficient design and correctness of transformations of source input to target output.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Program faults caused by incorrect compiler behavior can be very difficult to track down and work around; therefore, compiler implementers invest significant effort to ensure compiler correctness.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] With respect to making source code runnable, an interpreter provides a similar function as a compiler, but via a different mechanism.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] An interpreter executes code without converting it to machine code.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Therefore, some interpreters execute source code while others execute an intermediate form such as bytecode.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] A program compiled to native code tends to run faster than when interpreted, while environments with a bytecode-intermediate-form tends toward intermediate-speed.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Alternatively, just-in-time compilation allows for native execution speed with a one-time startup processing time cost.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Low-level programming languages, such as assembly and C, are typically compiled, especially when speed is a significant concern, rather than having cross-platform support.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] For such languages, there are more one-to-one correspondences between the source code and the resulting machine code, making it easier for programmers to control the use of hardware.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] In theory, any programming language can be used via either a compiler or an interpreter, but in practice, languages tend to be used with only one or the other.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Nonetheless, it is possible to write a compiler for a language that is commonly interpreted.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] For example, Common Lisp can be compiled to Java bytecode (and then interpreted by the Java virtual machine), to C code (which can then be compiled again to native machine code), or directly to native code.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Theoretical computing concepts developed by scientists, mathematicians, and engineers formed the basis of digital modern computing development during World War II.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Primitive binary languages evolved because digital devices only understand ones and zeros and the circuit patterns in the underlying machine architecture.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] In the late 1940s, assembly languages were created to offer a more workable abstraction of the computer architectures.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Limited memory capacity of early computers led to substantial technical challenges when the first compilers were designed.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Therefore, the compiling process needed to be divided into several small programs.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The front end programs produce the analysis products used by the back end programs to generate target code.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] As computer technology provided more resources, compiler designs could align better with the compiling process.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] It is usually more productive for a programmer to use a high-level language, so the development of high-level languages followed naturally from the abilities offered by digital computers.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] High-level languages are formal languages that are strictly defined by their syntax and semantics which form the high-level language architecture.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The sentences in a language may be defined by a set of rules called a grammar.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Backus–Naur form (BNF) describes the syntax of "sentences" of a language.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] It was developed by John Backus and used for the syntax of Algol 60.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The ideas derive from the context-free grammar concepts by linguist Noam Chomsky.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] "BNF and its extensions have become standard tools for describing the syntax of programming notations.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Between 1942 and 1945, Konrad Zuse designed the first (algorithmic) programming language for computers named *Plankalkül* ("Plan Calculus").
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Zuse also envisioned a *Planfertigungsgerät* ("Plan assembly device") to automatically translate the mathematical formulation of a program into machine-readable punched film stock.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] While no implementation occurred until the 1970s, it presented concepts later seen in APL designed by Ken Iverson in the late 1950s.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] APL is a language for mathematical computations.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Between 1949 and 1951, Heinz Rutishauser proposed Superplan, a high-level language and automatic translator.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] His ideas were later refined by Friedrich L.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Compiler technology evolved from the need for a strictly defined transformation of the high-level source program into a low-level target program for the digital computer.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The compiler could be viewed as a front end to deal with the analysis of the source code and a back end to synthesize the analysis into the target code.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Optimization between the front end and back end could produce more efficient target code.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Early operating systems and software were written in assembly language.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] In the 1960s and early 1970s, the use of high-level languages for system programming was still controversial due to resource limitations.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] However, several research and industry efforts began the shift toward high-level systems programming languages, for example, BCPL, BLISS, B, and C.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] BCPL (Basic Combined Programming Language) designed in 1966 by Martin Richards at the University of Cambridge was originally developed as a compiler writing tool.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Several compilers have been implemented, Richards' book provides insights to the language and its compiler.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] BCPL was not only an influential systems programming language that is still used in research but also provided a basis for the design of B and C languages.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] BLISS (Basic Language for Implementation of System Software) was developed for a Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-10 computer by W.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Wulf's Carnegie Mellon University (CMU) research team.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The CMU team went on to develop BLISS-11 compiler one year later in 1970.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Multics (Multiplexed Information and Computing Service), a time-sharing operating system project, involved MIT, Bell Labs, General Electric (later Honeywell) and was led by Fernando Corbató from MIT.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Multics was written in the PL/I language developed by IBM and IBM User Group.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] IBM's goal was to satisfy business, scientific, and systems programming requirements.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] There were other languages that could have been considered but PL/I offered the most complete solution even though it had not been implemented.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] For the first few years of the Multics project, a subset of the language could be compiled to assembly language with the Early PL/I (EPL) compiler by Doug McIlory and Bob Morris from Bell Labs.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] EPL supported the project until a boot-strapping compiler for the full PL/I could be developed.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Bell Labs left the Multics project in 1969, and developed a system programming language B based on BCPL concepts, written by Dennis Ritchie and Ken Thompson.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Ritchie created a boot-strapping compiler for B and wrote Unics (Uniplexed Information and Computing Service) operating system for a PDP-7 in B.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Bell Labs started the development and expansion of C based on B and BCPL.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The BCPL compiler had been transported to Multics by Bell Labs and BCPL was a preferred language at Bell Labs.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Initially, a front-end program to Bell Labs' B compiler was used while a C compiler was developed.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] In 1971, a new PDP-11 provided the resource to define extensions to B and rewrite the compiler.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] By 1973 the design of C language was essentially complete and the Unix kernel for a PDP-11 was rewritten in C.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Steve Johnson started development of Portable C Compiler (PCC) to support retargeting of C compilers to new machines.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Object-oriented programming (OOP) offered some interesting possibilities for application development and maintenance.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] OOP concepts go further back but were part of LISP and Simula language science.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Bell Labs became interested in OOP with the development of C++.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] C++ was first used in 1980 for systems programming.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The initial design leveraged C language systems programming abilities with Simula concepts.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Object-oriented facilities were added in 1983.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The Cfront program implemented a C++ front-end for C84 language compiler.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] In subsequent years several C++ compilers were developed as C++ popularity grew.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] In many application domains, the idea of using a higher-level language quickly caught on.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Because of the expanding functionality supported by newer programming languages and the increasing complexity of computer architectures, compilers became more complex.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] DARPA (Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency) sponsored a compiler project with Wulf's CMU research team in 1970.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The Production Quality Compiler-Compiler PQCC design would produce a Production Quality Compiler (PQC) from formal definitions of source language and the target.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] PQCC tried to extend the term compiler-compiler beyond the traditional meaning as a parser generator (e.g., Yacc) without much success.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] PQCC might more properly be referred to as a compiler generator.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] PQCC research into code generation process sought to build a truly automatic compiler-writing system.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The effort discovered and designed the phase structure of the PQC.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The BLISS-11 compiler provided the initial structure.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The phases included analyses (front end), intermediate translation to virtual machine (middle end), and translation to the target (back end).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] TCOL was developed for the PQCC research to handle language specific constructs in the intermediate representation.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Variations of TCOL supported various languages.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The PQCC project investigated techniques of automated compiler construction.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The design concepts proved useful in optimizing compilers and compilers for the (since 1995, object-oriented) programming language Ada.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The Ada *STONEMAN* document formalized the program support environment (APSE) along with the kernel (KAPSE) and minimal (MAPSE).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] An Ada interpreter NYU/ED supported development and standardization efforts with the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) and the International Standards Organization (ISO).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Initial Ada compiler development by the U.S.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Military Services included the compilers in a complete integrated design environment along the lines of the *STONEMAN* document.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Army and Navy worked on the Ada Language System (ALS) project targeted to DEC/VAX architecture while the Air Force started on the Ada Integrated Environment (AIE) targeted to IBM 370 series.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] While the projects did not provide the desired results, they did contribute to the overall effort on Ada development.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Other Ada compiler efforts got underway in Britain at the University of York and in Germany at the University of Karlsruhe.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] S., Verdix (later acquired by Rational) delivered the Verdix Ada Development System (VADS) to the Army.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] VADS provided a set of development tools including a compiler.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Unix/VADS could be hosted on a variety of Unix platforms such as DEC Ultrix and the Sun 3/60 Solaris targeted to Motorola 68020 in an Army CECOM evaluation.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] There were soon many Ada compilers available that passed the Ada Validation tests.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The Free Software Foundation GNU project developed the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) which provides a core capability to support multiple languages and targets.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The Ada version GNAT is one of the most widely used Ada compilers.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] GNAT is free but there is also commercial support, for example, AdaCore, was founded in 1994 to provide commercial software solutions for Ada.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] GNAT Pro includes the GNU GCC based GNAT with a tool suite to provide an integrated development environment.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] High-level languages continued to drive compiler research and development.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Focus areas included optimization and automatic code generation.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Trends in programming languages and development environments influenced compiler technology.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] More compilers became included in language distributions (PERL, Java Development Kit) and as a component of an IDE (VADS, Eclipse, Ada Pro).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The interrelationship and interdependence of technologies grew.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The advent of web services promoted growth of web languages and scripting languages.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Scripts trace back to the early days of Command Line Interfaces (CLI) where the user could enter commands to be executed by the system.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] User Shell concepts developed with languages to write shell programs.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Early Windows designs offered a simple batch programming capability.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The conventional transformation of these language used an interpreter.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] While not widely used, Bash and Batch compilers have been written.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] More recently sophisticated interpreted languages became part of the developers tool kit.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Modern scripting languages include PHP, Python, Ruby and Lua.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] (Lua is widely used in game development.) All of these have interpreter and compiler support.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] "When the field of compiling began in the late 50s, its focus was limited to the translation of high-level language programs into machine code ...
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The compiler field is increasingly intertwined with other disciplines including computer architecture, programming languages, formal methods, software engineering, and computer security." The "Compiler Research: The Next 50 Years" article noted the importance of object-oriented languages and Java.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Security and parallel computing were cited among the future research targets.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] A compiler implements a formal transformation from a high-level source program to a low-level target program.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Compiler design can define an end-to-end solution or tackle a defined subset that interfaces with other compiling tools e.g., preprocessors, assemblers, linkers.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Design requirements include rigorously defined interfaces both internally between compiler components and externally between supporting toolsets.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] In the early days, the approach taken to compiler design was directly affected by the complexity of the computer language to be processed, the experience of the person(s) designing it, and the resources available.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Resource limitations led to the need to pass through the source code more than once.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] A compiler for a relatively simple language written by one person might be a single, monolithic piece of software.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] However, as the source language grows in complexity the design may be split into a number of interdependent phases.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Separate phases provide design improvements that focus development on the functions in the compiling process.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Classifying compilers by number of passes has its background in the hardware resource limitations of computers.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Compiling involves performing much work and early computers did not have enough memory to contain one program that did all of this work.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] As a result, compilers were split up into smaller programs which each made a pass over the source (or some representation of it) performing some of the required analysis and translations.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The ability to compile in a single pass has classically been seen as a benefit because it simplifies the job of writing a compiler and one-pass compilers generally compile source code faster than multi-pass compilers.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Thus, partly driven by the resource limits of early systems, many early languages were specifically designed so that they could be compiled in one pass (e.g., Pascal).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] In some cases, the design of a language feature may require a compiler to perform more than one pass over the source.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] For example, consider a declaration appearing on line 20 of the source which affects the translation of a statement appearing on line 10.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] In this case, the first pass needs to gather information about declarations appearing after statements that they affect, with the translation then performed during a subsequent pass.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The disadvantage of compiling in a single pass is that it is not possible to perform many of the sophisticated optimizations needed to generate high quality code.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] It can be difficult to count exactly how many passes an optimizing compiler makes.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] For instance, different phases of optimization may analyse one expression many times but only analyse another expression once.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Splitting a compiler up into small programs is a technique used by researchers interested in producing provably correct compilers.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Proving the correctness of a set of small programs often requires less effort than proving the correctness of a larger, single, equivalent program.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Regardless of the exact number of phases in the compiler design, the phases can be assigned to one of three stages.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The stages include a front end, a middle end, and a back end.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] This front/middle/back-end approach makes it possible to combine front ends for different languages with back ends for different CPUs while sharing the optimizations of the middle end.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Practical examples of this approach are the GNU Compiler Collection, Clang (LLVM-based C/C++ compiler), and the Amsterdam Compiler Kit, which have multiple front-ends, shared optimizations and multiple back-ends.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The front end analyzes the source code to build an internal representation of the program, called the intermediate representation (IR).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] It also manages the symbol table, a data structure mapping each symbol in the source code to associated information such as location, type and scope.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] While the frontend can be a single monolithic function or program, as in a scannerless parser, it was traditionally implemented and analyzed as several phases, which may execute sequentially or concurrently.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] This method is favored due to its modularity and separation of concerns.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Most commonly, the frontend is broken into three phases: lexical analysis (also known as lexing or scanning), syntax analysis (also known as scanning or parsing), and semantic analysis.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Lexing and parsing comprise the syntactic analysis (word syntax and phrase syntax, respectively), and in simple cases, these modules (the lexer and parser) can be automatically generated from a grammar for the language, though in more complex cases these require manual modification.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The lexical grammar and phrase grammar are usually context-free grammars, which simplifies analysis significantly, with context-sensitivity handled at the semantic analysis phase.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The semantic analysis phase is generally more complex and written by hand, but can be partially or fully automated using attribute grammars.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] These phases themselves can be further broken down: lexing as scanning and evaluating, and parsing as building a concrete syntax tree (CST, parse tree) and then transforming it into an abstract syntax tree (AST, syntax tree).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] In some cases additional phases are used, notably *line reconstruction* and *preprocessing,* but these are rare.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The middle end, also known as *optimizer,* performs optimizations on the intermediate representation in order to improve the performance and the quality of the produced machine code.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The middle end contains those optimizations that are independent of the CPU architecture being targeted.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Compiler analysis is the prerequisite for any compiler optimization, and they tightly work together.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] For example, dependence analysis is crucial for loop transformation.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The scope of compiler analysis and optimizations vary greatly; their scope may range from operating within a basic block, to whole procedures, or even the whole program.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] There is a trade-off between the granularity of the optimizations and the cost of compilation.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] For example, peephole optimizations are fast to perform during compilation but only affect a small local fragment of the code, and can be performed independently of the context in which the code fragment appears.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] In contrast, interprocedural optimization requires more compilation time and memory space, but enable optimizations that are only possible by considering the behavior of multiple functions simultaneously.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Interprocedural analysis and optimizations are common in modern commercial compilers from HP, IBM, SGI, Intel, Microsoft, and Sun Microsystems.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The free software GCC was criticized for a long time for lacking powerful interprocedural optimizations, but it is changing in this respect.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Another open source compiler with full analysis and optimization infrastructure is Open64, which is used by many organizations for research and commercial purposes.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Due to the extra time and space needed for compiler analysis and optimizations, some compilers skip them by default.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Users have to use compilation options to explicitly tell the compiler which optimizations should be enabled.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The back end is responsible for the CPU architecture specific optimizations and for code generation.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Compiler correctness is the branch of software engineering that deals with trying to show that a compiler behaves according to its language specification.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Techniques include developing the compiler using formal methods and using rigorous testing (often called compiler validation) on an existing compiler.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Higher-level programming languages usually appear with a type of translation in mind: either designed as compiled language or interpreted language.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] However, in practice there is rarely anything about a language that *requires* it to be exclusively compiled or exclusively interpreted, although it is possible to design languages that rely on re-interpretation at run time.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The categorization usually reflects the most popular or widespread implementations of a language.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] For instance, BASIC is sometimes called an interpreted language, and C a compiled one, despite the existence of BASIC compilers and C interpreters.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Interpretation does not replace compilation completely.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] It only hides it from the user and makes it gradual.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Even though an interpreter can itself be interpreted, a set of directly executed machine instructions is needed somewhere at the bottom of the execution stack (see machine language).
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Furthermore, for optimization compilers can contain interpreter functionality, and interpreters may include ahead of time compilation techniques.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] For example, where an expression can be executed during compilation and the results inserted into the output program, then it prevents it having to be recalculated each time the program runs, which can greatly speed up the final program.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Modern trends toward just-in-time compilation and bytecode interpretation at times blur the traditional categorizations of compilers and interpreters even further.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Meta-tracing is an automated compiler synthesis approach which takes this further and can be used to synthesize a compiler from a language interpreter.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Some language specifications spell out that implementations *must* include a compilation facility; for example, Common Lisp.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] However, there is nothing inherent in the definition of Common Lisp that stops it from being interpreted.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] To implement these features in a compiled language, programs must usually be shipped with a runtime library that includes a version of the compiler itself.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] One classification of compilers is by the platform on which their generated code executes.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] A *native* or *hosted* compiler is one whose output is intended to directly run on the same type of computer and operating system that the compiler itself runs on.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The output of a cross compiler is designed to run on a different platform.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Cross compilers are often used when developing software for embedded systems that are not intended to support a software development environment.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The output of a compiler that produces code for a virtual machine (VM) may or may not be executed on the same platform as the compiler that produced it.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] For this reason, such compilers are not usually classified as native or cross compilers.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The lower level language that is the target of a compiler may itself be a high-level programming language.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] C, viewed by some as a sort of portable assembly language, is frequently the target language of such compilers.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] For example, Cfront, the original compiler for C++, used C as its target language.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] The C code generated by such a compiler is usually not intended to be readable and maintained by humans, so indent style and creating pretty C intermediate code are ignored.
[src:mlir-compiler/compiler] Some of the features of C that make it a good target language include the `#line` directive, which can be generated by the compiler to support debugging of the original source, and the wide platform support available with C compilers.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] A **domain-specific language** (**DSL**) is a computer language specialized to a specific application domain.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] This is in contrast to a general-purpose language (GPL), which is broadly applicable across domains.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] There are a wide variety of DSLs, ranging from widely used languages for common domains, such as HTML for web pages, down to languages used by only one or a few pieces of software, such as MUSH soft code.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] DSLs can be further subdivided by the kind of language, and include domain-specific *markup* languages, domain-specific *modeling* languages (more generally, specification languages), and domain-specific *programming* languages.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Special-purpose computer languages have always existed in the computer age, but the term "domain-specific language" has become more popular due to the rise of domain-specific modeling.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Simpler DSLs, specifically ones used by a single application, are sometimes informally called **mini-languages**.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] For example, Perl was originally developed as a text-processing and glue language, for the same domain as AWK and shell scripts, but was mostly used as a general-purpose programming language later on.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] In contrast, PostScript is a Turing-complete language, and in principle can be used for any task, but in practice is narrowly used as a page description language.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The design and use of appropriate DSLs is a key part of domain engineering, by using a language suitable to the domain at hand – this may consist of using an existing DSL or GPL, or developing a new DSL.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Language-oriented programming considers the creation of special-purpose languages for expressing problems as standard part of the problem-solving process.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Pragmatically, a DSL may be specialized to a specific problem domain, a specific problem representation technique, a specific solution technique, or other aspects of a domain.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is created specifically to solve problems in a specific domain and is not intended to be able to solve problems outside of it (although that may be technically possible).
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] In contrast, general-purpose languages are created to solve problems in many domains.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is somewhere between a tiny programming language and a scripting language, and is often used in a way analogous to a programming library.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The boundaries between these concepts are quite blurry, much like the boundary between scripting languages and general-purpose languages.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages are languages (or often, declared syntaxes or grammars) with very specific goals in design and implementation.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language can be one of a visual diagramming language, such as those created by the Generic Eclipse Modeling System, programmatic abstractions, such as the Eclipse Modeling Framework, or textual languages.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] For instance, the command line utility grep has a regular expression syntax which matches patterns in lines of text.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The sed utility defines a syntax for matching and replacing regular expressions.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Often, these tiny languages can be used together inside a shell to perform more complex programming tasks.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The line between domain-specific languages and scripting languages is somewhat blurred, but domain-specific languages often lack low-level functions for file system access, interprocess control, and other functions that characterize full-featured programming languages, scripting or otherwise.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Further blurring this line, many domain-specific languages have exposed APIs, and can be accessed from other programming languages without breaking the flow of execution or calling a separate process, and can thus operate as programming libraries.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Some domain-specific languages expand over time to include full-featured programming tools, which further complicates the question of whether a language is domain-specific or not.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] In model-driven engineering, many examples of domain-specific languages may be found like Object Constraint Language (OCL), a language for decorating models with assertions or Query/View/Transformation (QVT), a domain-specific transformation language.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] However, languages like Unified Modeling Language (UML) are typically general-purpose modeling languages.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] To summarize, an analogy is useful: a *very little language* is like a knife, which can be used in thousands of different ways, from cutting food to self-defense.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] A *domain-specific language* is like an electric drill: it is a powerful tool with a wide variety of uses, but a specific context, namely, making holes in things.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] A *general purpose language* is a complete workbench, with a variety of tools intended for performing a variety of tasks.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages should be used by programmers who, looking at their current workbench, realize they need a better drill and find that a given domain-specific language provides exactly that.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] DSLs implemented via an independent interpreter or compiler are termed *external domain specific languages*.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] A separate category termed *embedded (or internal) domain specific languages* are typically implemented within a host language as a library and tend to be limited to the syntax of the host language, though this depends on host language abilities.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Adopting a domain-specific language approach to software engineering involves both risks and opportunities.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The well-designed domain-specific language manages to find the proper balance between these.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] GML is a domain-specific language used by GameMaker Studio designed to help novice programmers learn the fundamentals of coding more easily.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] It functions as a blend of several languages, including Delphi, C++, and BASIC.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Most GML functions, once compiled, call runtime functions written in the specific language of the target platform; consequently, their final implementation remains hidden from the user.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The language's primary goal is to lower the barrier to entry for game development.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The GameMaker runtime, which manages the main game loop and handles function implementation, allows a simple game to use only a few lines of code instead of thousands.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] ColdFusion's associated scripting language is another example of a domain-specific language for data-driven websites.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The language is used to weave together languages and services such as Java, .NET, C++, SMS, email, email servers, http, ftp, exchange, directory services, and file systems for use in websites.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The ColdFusion Markup Language (CFML) includes a set of tags that can be used in ColdFusion pages to interact with data sources, manipulate data, and display output.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] CFML tag syntax is similar to HTML element syntax.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Although the FilterMeister language reproduces a significant portion of the C language and function library, it contains only those features which can be used within the context of Photoshop plug-ins and adds a number of specific features only useful in this specific domain.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The *Template* feature of MediaWiki is an embedded domain-specific language whose fundamental purpose is to support the creation of page templates and the transclusion (inclusion by reference) of MediaWiki pages into other MediaWiki pages.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] There has been much interest in domain-specific languages to improve the productivity and quality of software engineering.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific language could possibly provide a robust set of tools for efficient software engineering.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Such tools are beginning to make their way into the development of critical software systems.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The Software Cost Reduction Toolkit is an example of this.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] A newer development is language-oriented programming, an integrated software engineering methodology based mainly on creating, optimizing, and using domain-specific languages.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Complementing language-oriented programming, and all other forms of domain-specific languages, are the class of compiler writing tools called metacompilers.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Such compiler is useful for generating parsers and code generators for domain-specific languages, and a metacompiler compiles a domain-specific metalanguage specifically designed for the domain of metaprogramming.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Besides parsing domain-specific languages, metacompilers are useful for generating a wide range of software engineering and analysis tools.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The meta-compiler methodology is often found in program transformation systems.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Metacompilers that played a significant role in both computer science and the computer industry include META II, and its descendant TreeMeta.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Unreal and Unreal Tournament unveiled a language named UnrealScript.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] This allowed rapid development of modifications relative to the competitor Quake (using the Id Tech 2 engine).
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The Id Tech engine used standard C code meaning C had to be learned and properly applied, while UnrealScript was optimized for ease of use and efficiency.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Similarly, more recent games have introduced their own specific languages for development.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] One more common example is Lua for scripting.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Various business rules engines have been developed for automating policy and business rules used in both government and private industry.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] ILOG, Oracle Policy Automation, DTRules, Drools and others provide support for DSLs aimed to support various problem domains.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] DTRules goes so far as to define an interface for the use of multiple DSLs within a rule set.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The purpose of business rules engines is to define a representation of business logic in as human-readable fashion as possible.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] This allows both subject-matter experts and developers to work with and understand the same representation of the business logic.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Most rules engines provide both an approach to simplifying the control structures for business logic (for example, using declarative rules or decision tables) coupled with alternatives to programming syntax in favor of DSLs.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Statistical modelers have developed domain-specific languages such as R (an implementation of the S language), Bugs, Jags, and Stan.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] These languages provide a syntax for describing a Bayesian model and generate a method for solving it using simulation.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Generate object handling and services based on an Interface Description Language for a domain-specific language such as JavaScript for web applications, HTML for documentation, C++ for high-performance code, etc.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] This is done by cross-language frameworks such as Apache Thrift or Google Protocol Buffers.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Gherkin is a language designed to define test cases to check the behavior of software, without specifying how that behavior is implemented.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] It is meant to be read and used by non-technical users using a natural language syntax and a line-oriented design.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] The tests defined with Gherkin must then be implemented in a general programming language.
[src:mlir-compiler/domain-specific-language] Then, the steps in a Gherkin program acts as a syntax for method invocation accessible to non-developers.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] An **intermediate representation** (**IR**) is the data structure or code used internally by a compiler or virtual machine to represent source code.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] An IR is designed to be conducive to further processing, such as optimization and translation.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] A "good" IR must be *accurate* – capable of representing the source code without loss of information – and *independent* of any particular source or target language.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] An IR may take one of several forms: an in-memory data structure, or a special tuple- or stack-based code readable by the program.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] In the latter case it is also called an *intermediate language*.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] A canonical example is found in most modern compilers.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] For example, the CPython interpreter transforms the linear human-readable text representing a program into an intermediate graph structure that allows flow analysis and re-arrangement before execution.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] Use of an intermediate representation such as this allows compiler systems like the GNU Compiler Collection and LLVM to be used by many different source languages to generate code for many different target architectures.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] An **intermediate language** is the language of an abstract machine designed to aid in the analysis of computer programs.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] The term comes from their use in compilers, where the source code of a program is translated into a form more suitable for code-improving transformations before being used to generate object or machine code for a target machine.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] A popular format for intermediate languages is three-address code.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] The term is also used to refer to languages used as intermediates by some high-level programming languages which do not output object or machine code themselves, but output the intermediate language only.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] This intermediate language is submitted to a compiler for such language, which then outputs finished object or machine code.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] This is usually done to ease the process of optimization or to increase portability by using an intermediate language that has compilers for many processors and operating systems, such as C.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] Languages used for this fall in complexity between high-level languages and low-level languages, such as assembly languages.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] Variants of C have been designed to provide C's features as a portable assembly language, including C-- and the C Intermediate Language.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] The GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) uses several intermediate languages internally to simplify portability and cross-compilation.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] The LLVM compiler framework is based on the LLVM IR intermediate language, of which the compact, binary serialized representation is also referred to as "bitcode" and has been productized by Apple.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] Like GIMPLE Bytecode, LLVM Bitcode is useful in link-time optimization.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] Like GCC, LLVM also targets some IRs meant for direct distribution, including Google's PNaCl IR and SPIR.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] A further development within LLVM is the use of *Multi-Level Intermediate Representation* (MLIR) with the potential to generate code for different heterogeneous targets, and to combine the outputs of different compilers.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] The ILOC intermediate language is used in classes on compiler design as a simple target language.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] Static analysis tools often use an intermediate representation.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] For instance, Radare2 is a toolbox for binary files analysis and reverse-engineering.
[src:mlir-compiler/intermediate-representation] It uses the intermediate languages ESIL and REIL to analyze binary files.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM is written in C++ and is designed for compile-time, link-time, and runtime optimization.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The LLVM project started in 2000 at the University of Illinois Urbana–Champaign, under the direction of Vikram Adve and Chris Lattner.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM was originally developed as a research infrastructure to investigate dynamic compilation techniques for static and dynamic programming languages.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM was released under the University of Illinois/NCSA Open Source License, a permissive free software licence.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] In 2005, Apple Inc. hired Lattner and formed a team to work on the LLVM system for various uses within Apple's development systems.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM has been an integral part of Apple's Xcode development tools for macOS and iOS since Xcode 4 in 2011.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] In 2006, Lattner started working on a new project named Clang.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The combination of the Clang frontend and LLVM backend is named Clang/LLVM or simply Clang.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The name *LLVM* was originally an initialism for *Low Level Virtual Machine*.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] However, the LLVM project evolved into an umbrella project that has little relationship to what most current developers think of as a virtual machine.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] This made the initialism "confusing" and "inappropriate", and since 2011 LLVM is "officially no longer an acronym", but a brand that applies to the LLVM umbrella project.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The project encompasses the LLVM intermediate representation (IR), the LLVM debugger, the LLVM implementation of the C++ Standard Library (with full support of C++11 and C++14), etc.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM is administered by the LLVM Foundation.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Compiler engineer Tanya Lattner became its president in 2014 and was still president and Executive Director as of November 2025.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The project was originally available under the UIUC license.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] After v9.0.0 released in 2019, LLVM relicensed to the Apache License 2.0 with LLVM Exceptions.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] As of November 2022 about 400 contributions had not been relicensed.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM can provide the middle layers of a complete compiler system, taking intermediate representation (IR) code from a compiler and emitting an optimized IR.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] This new IR can then be converted and linked into machine-dependent assembly language code for a target platform.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM can accept the IR from the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) toolchain, allowing it to be used with a wide array of extant compiler front-ends written for that project.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM can also be built with gcc after version 7.5.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM can also generate relocatable machine code at compile-time or link-time or even binary machine code at runtime.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM supports a language-independent instruction set and type system.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Each instruction is in static single assignment form (SSA), meaning that each variable (called a typed register) is assigned once and then frozen.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] This helps simplify the analysis of dependencies among variables.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM allows code to be compiled statically, as it is under the traditional GCC system, or left for late-compiling from the IR to machine code via just-in-time compilation (JIT), similar to Java.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The type system consists of basic types such as integer or floating-point numbers and five derived types: pointers, arrays, vectors, structures, and functions.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] A type construct in a concrete language can be represented by combining these basic types in LLVM.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] For example, a class in C++ can be represented by a mix of structures, functions and arrays of function pointers.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The LLVM JIT compiler can optimize unneeded static branches out of a program at runtime, and thus is useful for partial evaluation in cases where a program has many options, most of which can easily be determined unneeded in a specific environment.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] This feature is used in the OpenGL pipeline of Mac OS X Leopard (v10.5) to provide support for missing hardware features.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Graphics code within the OpenGL stack can be left in intermediate representation and then compiled when run on the target machine.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] On systems with high-end graphics processing units (GPUs), the resulting code remains quite thin, passing the instructions on to the GPU with minimal changes.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] On systems with low-end GPUs, LLVM will compile optional procedures that run on the local central processing unit (CPU) that emulate instructions that the GPU cannot run internally.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM improved performance on low-end machines using Intel GMA chipsets.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] A similar system was developed under the Gallium3D LLVMpipe, and incorporated into the GNOME shell to allow it to run without a proper 3D hardware driver loaded.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] In 2011, programs compiled by GCC outperformed those from LLVM by 10%, on average.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] In 2013, phoronix reported that LLVM had caught up with GCC, compiling binaries of approximately equal performance.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM has become an umbrella project containing multiple components.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM was originally written to be a replacement for the extant code generator in the GCC stack, and many of the GCC frontends were modified to work with it, resulting in the now-defunct LLVM-GCC suite.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The modifications generally involved a GIMPLE-to-LLVM IR step so that LLVM optimizers and codegen could be used instead of GCC's GIMPLE system.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Apple was a significant user of LLVM-GCC through Xcode 4.x (2013).
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] This use of the GCC frontend was considered a temporary measure; it became mostly obsolete with Apple's development of Clang, a newer compiler frontend, with a more modern, modular codebase and greater compilation speed, supporting C, C++, and Objective-C.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Support for LLVM-GCC was dropped in Xcode 5.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Primarily supported by Apple, Clang was aimed at replacing the C/Objective-C compiler in the GCC system with a system that is more easily integrated with integrated development environments (IDEs) and has wider support for multithreading.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Support for OpenMP directives has been included in Clang since release 3.8.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Widespread interest in LLVM has led to several efforts to develop new frontends for many other languages, including Ada, D, Delphi, Fortran, Haskell, Julia, Rust, Swift, and others.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The Utrecht Haskell compiler can generate code for LLVM.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] While the generator was in early stages of development, in many cases it was more efficient than the C code generator.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC) backend uses LLVM and achieves a 30% speed-up of compiled code relative to native code compiling via GHC or C code generation followed by compiling, missing only one of the many optimizing techniques implemented by the GHC.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Many other components are in various stages of development, including, but not limited to, a Java bytecode frontend, a Common Intermediate Language (CIL) frontend, the MacRuby implementation of Ruby 1.9, various frontends for Standard ML, and a new graph coloring register allocator.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The core of LLVM is the intermediate representation (IR), a low-level programming language similar to assembly.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] IR is a strongly typed reduced instruction set computer (RISC) instruction set which abstracts away most details of the target.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] For example, the calling convention is abstracted through `call` and `ret` instructions with explicit arguments.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Also, instead of a fixed set of registers, IR uses an infinite set of temporaries of the form %0, %1, etc.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM supports three equivalent forms of IR: a human-readable assembly format, an in-memory format suitable for frontends, and a dense bitcode format for serializing.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The many different conventions used and features provided by different targets mean that LLVM cannot truly produce a target-independent IR and retarget it without breaking some established rules.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Examples of target dependence beyond what is explicitly mentioned in the documentation can be found in a 2011 proposal for "wordcode", a fully target-independent variant of LLVM IR intended for online distribution.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The LLVM project also introduces another type of intermediate representation named MLIR which helps build reusable and extensible compiler infrastructure by employing a plugin architecture named Dialect.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] It enables the use of higher-level information on the program structure in the process of optimization including polyhedral compilation.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Some features are not available on some platforms.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Most features are present for IA-32, x86-64, z/Architecture, ARM, and PowerPC.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] In the past, LLVM also supported other backends, fully or partially, including C backend, Cell SPU, mblaze (MicroBlaze), AMD R600, DEC/Compaq Alpha (Alpha AXP) and Nios2, but that hardware is mostly obsolete, and LLVM developers decided the support and maintenance costs were no longer justified.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM also supports WebAssembly as a target, enabling compiled programs to execute in WebAssembly-enabled environments such as Google Chrome / Chromium, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Apple Safari or WAVM.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM-compliant WebAssembly compilers typically support mostly unmodified source code written in C, C++, D, Rust, Nim, Kotlin and several other languages.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The LLVM machine code (MC) subproject is LLVM's framework for translating machine instructions between textual forms and machine code.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Formerly, LLVM relied on the system assembler, or one provided by a toolchain, to translate assembly into machine code.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] LLVM MC's integrated assembler supports most LLVM targets, including IA-32, x86-64, ARM, and ARM64.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] For some targets, including the various MIPS instruction sets, integrated assembly support is usable but still in the beta stage.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The lld subproject is an attempt to develop a built-in, platform-independent linker for LLVM. lld aims to remove dependence on a third-party linker.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] As of May 2017, lld supports ELF, PE/COFF, Mach-O, and WebAssembly in descending order of completeness. lld is faster than both flavors of GNU ld.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Unlike the GNU linkers, lld has built-in support for link-time optimization (LTO).
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] This allows for faster code generation as it bypasses the use of a linker plugin, but on the other hand prohibits interoperability with other flavors of LTO.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] The LLVM project includes an implementation of the C++ Standard Library named libc++, dual-licensed under the MIT License and the UIUC license.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Since v9.0.0, it was relicensed to the Apache License 2.0 with LLVM Exceptions.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] This implements a suite of cache-locality optimizations as well as auto-parallelism and vectorization using a polyhedral model.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] llvm-libc is an incomplete, upcoming, ABI independent C standard library designed by and for the LLVM project.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] Due to its permissive license, many vendors release their own tuned forks of LLVM.
[src:mlir-compiler/llvm] This is officially recognized by LLVM's documentation, which suggests against using version numbers in feature checks for this reason.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] MLIR was originally developed in 2018 by Chris Lattner at Google, and publicly released as part of LLVM in 2019.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] MLIR is used in a range of systems including TensorFlow, Mojo, TPU-MLIR, and others.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] It is released under the Apache License 2.0 with LLVM exceptions and is maintained as part of the LLVM project.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Work on MLIR began in 2018, led by Chris Lattner at Google in collaboration with Mehdi Amini, River Riddle, and others, as a response to the growing complexity of modern compiler toolchains.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The project aimed to improve the modularity, composability, and maintainability of compiler infrastructures, particularly in domains such as machine learning, high-level synthesis, and hardware acceleration.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] It was formally introduced at the 2019 LLVM Developer Meeting and was open-sourced later that year as part of the LLVM monorepository.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] MLIR’s architecture was shaped by prior experiences building compilers such as XLA and LLVM, where limitations in existing intermediate representations hindered optimization and reuse across abstraction levels.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] To address this, MLIR introduced a novel concept of multi-level IRs that could coexist in the same system and be gradually lowered through well-defined transformations.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] A foundational design feature was the use of dialects, allowing different domains and hardware targets to define custom operations and type systems while maintaining interoperability.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Since its release, MLIR has been adopted by multiple compiler ecosystems and research efforts.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] In TensorFlow, MLIR serves as the foundation for rewriting and lowering transformations in components such as XLA and TensorFlow Runtime.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The language Mojo, developed by Modular Inc., relies on MLIR to achieve ahead-of-time compilation for artificial intelligence workloads.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] MLIR continues to evolve as part of the LLVM Project and follows the project's release schedule and development policies.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] It is developed collaboratively by contributors from industry, academia, and the broader open-source community.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] In MLIR, a **dialect** defines a self-contained namespace of operations, types, attributes, and other constructs.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Dialects are the primary mechanism for extensibility, allowing developers to introduce domain-specific abstractions while maintaining compatibility within the broader MLIR framework.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Each operation within a dialect is identified by a unique name and may include optional operands, results, attributes, and regions.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Operands and results follow the static single-assignment form (SSA), and each result is associated with a type.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Attributes represent compile-time metadata, such as constant values.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Regions consist of ordered blocks, each of which may take input arguments and contain a sequence of nested operations.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] While MLIR is designed around SSA, it avoids traditional PHI nodes by using block arguments in conjunction with the operands of control-flow operations to model value merging.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] This operation, named `morph`, belongs to the `mydialect` dialect.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] It takes one input operand (`%input#3`) of type `custom_type` and produces two output values of type `other_type`.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The operation includes two attributes-`some.attribute` and `other_attribute`-and contains a region with a single block (`^bb0`) that accepts one argument.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The `loc` keyword specifies source-level location information, which can be used for debugging or diagnostic reporting.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The syntax of operations, types and attributes can also be customized according to the user preferences by implementing proper parsing and printing functions within the operation definition.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The MLIR dialects ecosystem is open and extensible, allowing end-users to define new dialects that capture the semantics of specific computational domains.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] At the same time, the MLIR codebase provides a variety of built-in dialects that address common patterns found in intermediate representations.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] These core dialects are designed to be self-contained and interoperable, making them suitable for reuse across different compiler stacks.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] For example, the `arith` dialect includes basic mathematical operations over integers and floating-point types, while the `memref` dialect provides operations for memory allocation and access.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Control-flow abstractions are handled by dialects such as `affine`, which supports affine loop nests suitable for polyhedral optimization, and `scf`, which provides structured control flow using constructs like `for`, `if`, and `while`.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The `func` dialect supports function definitions and calls, while the `gpu` dialect introduces primitives for GPU programming models.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Additionally, the `tosa` dialect defines a portable and quantization-friendly operator set for machine learning inference.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Finally, the `llvm` dialect provides a one-to-one mapping to LLVM IR, enabling seamless lowering to LLVM’s backend and reuse of its optimization and code generation infrastructure.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Although different dialects may be used to express similar computations, the level of abstraction and the intended compilation flow may vary.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] In the example above, the `affine` dialect enables polyhedral analysis and optimizations, while the `memref` and `arith` dialects express memory and arithmetic operations, respectively.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The operations of a dialect can be defined using the C++ language, but also in a more convenient and robust way by using the Operation definition specification (ODS).
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] By using TableGen, the C++ code for declarations and definitions can be then automatically generated.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The same declaration mechanism can be used also for types and attributes, which are the other two categories of elements constituting a dialect.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The following example illustrates how to specify the *assembly format* of an operation expecting a variadic number of operands and producing zero results.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The textual representation consists in the optional list of attributes, followed by the optional list of operands, a colon, and types of the operands.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Transformations can always be performed directly on the IR, without having to rely on built-in coordination mechanisms.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] However, in order to ease both implementation and maintenance, MLIR provides an infrastructure for IR rewriting that is composed by different rewrite drivers.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Each driver receives a set of objects named *patterns*, each of which has its own internal logic to match operations with certain properties.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] When an operation is matched, the rewrite process is performed and the IR is modified according to the logic within the pattern.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] This driver operates according to the *legality* of existing operations, meaning that the driver receives a set of rules determining which operations have to be considered *illegal* and expects the patterns to match and convert them into *legal* ones.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The logic behind those rules can be arbitrarily complex: it may be based just on the dialect to which the operations belong, but can also inspect more specific properties such as attributes or nested operations.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] As the names suggests, this driver is typically used for converting the operations of a dialect into operations belonging to a different one.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] In this scenario, the whole source dialect would be marked as illegal, the destination one as legal, and patterns for the source dialect operations would be provided.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The dialect conversion framework also provides support for type conversion, which has to be performed on operands and results to convert them to the type system of the destination dialect.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] MLIR allows for multiple conversion paths to be taken.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The driver greedily applies the provided patterns according to their benefit, until a fixed point is reached or the maximum number of iterations is reached.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The benefit of a pattern is self-attributed.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] In case of equalities, the relative order within the patterns list is used.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] MLIR allows to apply existing optimizations (e.g., common subexpression elimination, loop-invariant code motion) on custom dialects by means of traits and interfaces.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] These two mechanisms enable transformation passes to operate on operations without knowing their actual implementation, relying only on some properties that traits or interfaces provide.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Traits are meant to be attached to operations without requiring any additional implementation.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Their purpose is to indicate that the operation satisfies certain properties (e.g. having exactly two operands).
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Interfaces, instead, represent a more powerful tool through which the operation can be queried about some specific aspect, whose value may change between instances of the same kind of operation.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] An example of interface is the representation of memory effects: each operation that operates on memory may have such interface attached, but the actual effects may depend on the actual operands (e.g., a function call with arguments possibly being constants or references to memory).
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] The freedom in modeling intermediate representations enables MLIR to be used in a wide range of scenarios.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] This includes traditional programming languages, but also high-level synthesis, quantum computing and homomorphic encryption.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] Machine learning applications also take advantage of built-in polyhedral compilation techniques, together with dialects targeting accelerators and other heterogeneous systems.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] For specific compiler projects and toolchains built using MLIR, see the Ecosystem section below.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] MLIR has fostered a growing ecosystem of open-source projects, production compilers, and experimental toolchains across multiple domains.
[src:mlir-compiler/mlir-software] These projects demonstrate MLIR’s flexibility in modeling, optimizing, and lowering computations for a diverse set of hardware targets.
